	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">the Gameboy had quite a bit of resources available for programming homebrew. There is no reason there would be less of that now.</div>
<br />Other than perhaps fewer people still having working flash cards and writers? A lot of the community went to the GBA for several reasons: <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>The GBA's CPU is more friendly to the abstractions of C. </li><li>People were already buying GBA flash cards to make their own no-repeat 100-in-1 pirate multis in PocketNES. </li><li>It took until the GBA era for the Chinese flash card market to figure out the whack-a-mole pattern. Once Bung got whacked, GBC homebrew kind of died. But once Visoly got whacked, three more popped up (F2A, EZ-Flash, and EFA-Linker). </li></ol>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


